<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-27T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-27T10:00:00-05:00" n="368" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/2359</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MJVA1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-27T23:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">July 27,
                                            1918, 11 p.m.</hi></date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received July 28, 1.50
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>My telegram of July 24, 5 p.m. A memorandum from the Foreign Office
                                announces that the Chinese Government consents that the
                                Czecho-Slovak Army shall enjoy unrestricted freedom in the use of
                                the Chinese Eastern Railway.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_MJVA1"><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>